instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "During the development of a Digital Twin, a multi‑layered MBSE approach is employed. Modeling is performed at progressively lower abstraction levels – starting from a requirements model, moving to functional and logical architectures, and finally to the product/technical layer. SysML (version 1.7) with IBDs, together with architecture description languages such as ACME, AADL, and MontiArc, is used to describe the component‑and‑connector structure, defining components, interfaces, and interconnections. Logical behaviour is captured via MontiArc automata or SysML state machines, which are then linked to executable simulations in MathWorks Simulink or to source code written in C++ or Java. Transition management across these phases is achieved through model migration and traceability, while lifecycle governance is governed by the chosen MBSE methodology, e.g. RFLP, OOSEM, SPES, or SMArDT."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity is quantified by the maximum geometric deviation between the CAD model and the assembled robot, which is maintained below 0.5 mm RMS across the workspace. Behavioural fidelity is validated by comparing Simulink simulation outputs to experimental step‑response data; the residual error remains under 2 % of full‑scale motion. Uncertainty sources – mechanical backlash, encoder quantisation, temperature drift, and motor hysteresis – are modelled as bounded random variables and propagated through the state‑space representation; the resulting covariance matrix is used to compute confidence intervals for real‑time pose estimation. Error detection includes a periodic health check that cross‑matches encoder readings with an independent inertial measurement unit, flagging discrepancies above a 3σ threshold. Data integrity is enforced by checksum (CRC‑32) at the packet level, and any corrupted packets trigger automatic retransmission. Overall, a continuous integration pipeline rebuilds the simulation model and re‑validates against a library of benchmark tests nightly, ensuring adherence to ISO 13849 safety and IEC 61508 functional safety standards."
]
